    "troubleshooting_example": "Speed-reference not responding via the potentiometer on AI1: this sheet shows the pot fed by the +10V reference (CN6 '10V') with its wiper to AI1 and return to COM. First measure the 10V terminal to COM — a good ~10V proves the drive's reference supply is healthy. Then measure AI1 to COM while turning the pot: it should sweep from ~0V to ~10V (0..10Vdc as printed). If 10V is present but AI1 does not vary, the fault is in the potentiometer or its wiring, not the drive; if the 10V terminal itself reads dead, the drive's reference supply/board is at fault. Note: this sheet is a wiring reference only — it does not show the drive's internal parameter/logic behavior, so what the drive DOES with the reference must be confirmed in its parameters, not from this print.",
    "safety_context": "The power terminals (CN1 line, CN10 motor, CN9 PA/+/PC/- DC bus) are lethal live parts; the DC-bus capacitors can hold a dangerous charge AFTER the mains disconnect, so treat PA/+/PC/- and the braking terminals as energized until proven discharged. This sheet does NOT print the actual line/motor voltage — determine it from the drive rating plate before working. For continuity/resistance checks (e.g. motor leads, resistor), de-energize, lock out, and verify absence of voltage including the DC bus. The only voltage values actually printed here are the control-side references: ±10Vdc and 0..10Vdc analog, 24V/0V, 5V, 10V and the 1Vpp encoder signal — for live checks on those use appropriately rated meters and energized-work procedures. Terminal screw torque printed as 0.5 N·m / 4.4 lb·in.",
